# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anabolism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:anabolism/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The process may be likened to how yeast ferments sugars to produce ethanol for wine, beer, or fuel, but the organisms that carry out the ABE fermentation are strictly anaerobic (obligate anaerobes).
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation produces solvents in a ratio of 3 parts acetone, 6 parts butanol to 1 part ethanol.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It usually uses a strain of bacteria from class Clostridia (family Clostridiaceae).
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] *Clostridium acetobutylicum* is the most well-studied and widely used.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Although less effective, *Clostridium beijerinckii* and *Clostridium saccharobutylicum* bacterial strains have shown good results as well.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation pathway generally proceeds in two phases.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In the initial acidogenesis phase, the cells grow exponentially and accumulate acetate and butyrate.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The low pH along with other factors then trigger a metabolic shift to the solventogenesis phase, in which acetate and butyrate are used to produce the solvents.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For gas stripping, the most common gases used are the off-gases from the fermentation itself, a mixture of carbon dioxide and hydrogen gas.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The production of butanol by biological means was first performed by Louis Pasteur in 1861.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In 1905, Austrian biochemist Franz Schardinger found that acetone could similarly be produced.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In 1910 Auguste Fernbach (1860–1939) developed a bacterial fermentation process using potato starch as a feedstock in the production of butanol.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Industrial exploitation of ABE fermentation started in 1916, during World War I, with Chaim Weizmann's isolation of Clostridium acetobutylicum, as described in U.S. patent 1315585.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The Weizmann process was operated by Commercial Solvents Corporation from about 1920 to 1964 with plants in the US (Terre Haute, IN, and Peoria, IL), and Liverpool, England.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The Peoria plant was the largest of the three.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It used molasses as feedstock and had 96 fermenters with a volume of 96,000 gallons each.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] After World War II, ABE fermentation became generally non-profitable, compared to the production of the same three solvents (acetone, butanol, ethanol) from petroleum.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] During the 1950s and 1960s, ABE fermentation was replaced by petroleum chemical plants.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Due to different raw material costs, ABE fermentation was viable in South Africa until the early 1980s, with the last plant closing in 1983.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Green Biologics Ltd operated the last attempt to resurrect the process at scale but the plant closed in Minnesota in June 2019.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] A new ABE biorefinery has been developed in Scotland by Celtic Renewables Ltd and began production in 2023.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The key difference in the process is the use of low value spent materials or residues from other processes removing the variable costs of raw feedstock crops and materials.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The most critical aspect in biomass fermentation processes is related to its productivity.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation via *Clostridium beijerinckii* or *Clostridium acetobutylicum* for instance is characterized by product inhibition.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] This means that there is a product concentration threshold that cannot be overcome, resulting in a product stream highly diluted in water.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this reason, in order to have a comparable productivity and profitability with respect to the petrochemical processes, cost and energy effective solutions for the product purification sections are required to provide a significant product recovery at the desired purity.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In the second half of the 20th century, these technologies allowed an increase in the final product concentration in the broth from 15 to 30 g/L, an increase in the final productivity from 0.46 to 4.6 g/(L*h) and an increase in the yield from 15 to 42%.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] From a compound purification perspective, the main criticalities in the ABE/W product recovery are due to the water–alcohol mixture's non-ideal interactions leading to homogeneous and heterogeneous azeotropic species, as shown by the ternary equilibrium diagram.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] This causes the separation by standard distillation to be particularly impractical but, on the other hand, allows the exploitation of the liquid–liquid demixing region both for analogous and alternative separation processes.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Therefore, in order to enhance the ABE fermentation yield, mainly in situ product recovery systems have been developed.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] These include gas stripping, pervaporation, liquid–liquid extraction, distillation via Dividing Wall Column, membrane distillation, membrane separation, adsorption, and reverse osmosis.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Green Biologics Ltd. implemented many of these technologies at an industrial scale.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Moreover, differently from crude oil feedstocks, biomasses nature fluctuates over the year's seasons and according to the geographical location.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] ABE fermentation is attracting renewed interest with a focus on butanol as a renewable biofuel.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Sustainability is by far the topic of major concern over the last years.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The energy challenge is the key point of the environmental friendly policies adopted by all the most developed and industrialized countries worldwide.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this purpose Horizon 2020, the biggest EU Research and Innovation programme, was funded by the European Union over the 2014–2020 period.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The International Energy Agency defines renewables as the centre of the transition to a less carbon-intensive and more sustainable energy system.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Biofuels are believed to represent around 30% of energy consumption in transport by 2060.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Their role is particularly important in sectors which are difficult to decarbonise, such as aviation, shipping and other long-haul transport.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] That is why several bioprocesses have seen a renewed interest in recent years, both from a research and an industrial perspective.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this reason, the ABE fermentation process has been reconsidered from a different perspective.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Although it was originally conceived to produce acetone, it is considered as a suitable production pathway for biobutanol that has become the product of major interest.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Biogenic butanol is a possible substitute of bioethanol or even better and it is already employed both as fuel additive and as pure fuel instead of standard gasoline because, differently from ethanol, it can be directly and efficiently used in gasoline engines.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Moreover, it has the advantage that it can be shipped and distributed through existing pipelines and filling stations.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Finally biobutanol is widely used as a direct solvent for paints, coatings, varnishes, resins, dyes, camphor, vegetable oils, fats, waxes, shellac, rubbers and alkaloids due to its higher energy density, lower volatility, and lower hygroscopicity.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It can be produced from different kinds of cellulosic biomass and can be used for further processing of advanced biofuels such as butyl levulinate as well.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The application of n-butanol in the production of butyl acrylate has a wide scope for its expansion, which in turn would help in increasing the consumption of n-butanol globally.
[src:anabolism/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Butyl acrylate was the biggest n-butanol application in 2014 and is projected to be worth US$3.9 billion by 2020.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP can be interconverted to adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] ATP contains one more phosphate group than ADP, while AMP contains one fewer phosphate group.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] Energy transfer used by all living things is a result of dephosphorylation of ATP by enzymes known as ATPases.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] The cleavage of a phosphate group from ATP results in the coupling of energy to metabolic reactions and a by-product of ADP.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] ATP is continually reformed from lower-energy species ADP and AMP.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] The biosynthesis of ATP is achieved throughout processes such as substrate-level phosphorylation, oxidative phosphorylation, and photophosphorylation, all of which facilitate the addition of a phosphate group to ADP.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP cycling supplies the energy needed to do work in a biological system, the thermodynamic process of transferring energy from one source to another.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] There are two types of energy: potential energy and kinetic energy.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] Potential energy can be thought of as stored energy, or usable energy that is available to do work.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] Kinetic energy is the energy of an object as a result of its motion.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] The significance of ATP is in its ability to store potential energy within the phosphate bonds.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy stored between these bonds can then be transferred to do work.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] For example, the transfer of energy from ATP to the protein myosin causes a conformational change when connecting to actin during muscle contraction.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] It takes multiple reactions between myosin and actin to effectively produce one muscle contraction, and, therefore, the availability of large amounts of ATP is required to produce each muscle contraction.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] For this reason, biological processes have evolved to produce efficient ways to replenish the potential energy of ATP from ADP.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] Breaking one of ATP's phosphorus bonds generates approximately 30.5 kilojoules per mole of ATP (7.3 kcal).
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP can be converted, or powered back to ATP through the process of releasing the chemical energy available in food; in humans, this is constantly performed via aerobic respiration in the mitochondria.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] Plants use photosynthetic pathways to convert and store energy from sunlight, also conversion of ADP to ATP.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] Animals use the energy released in the breakdown of glucose and other molecules to convert ADP to ATP, which can then be used to fuel necessary growth and cell maintenance.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] The ten-step catabolic pathway of glycolysis is the initial phase of free-energy release in the breakdown of glucose and can be split into two phases, the preparatory phase and payoff phase.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP and phosphate are needed as precursors to synthesize ATP in the payoff reactions of the TCA cycle and oxidative phosphorylation mechanism.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] During the payoff phase of glycolysis, the enzymes phosphoglycerate kinase and pyruvate kinase facilitate the addition of a phosphate group to ADP by way of substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] Glycolysis is performed by all living organisms and consists of 10 steps.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 require the input of energy derived from the hydrolysis of ATP to ADP and Pi (inorganic phosphate), whereas steps 7 and 10 require the input of ADP, each yielding ATP.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] The enzymes necessary to break down glucose are found in the cytoplasm, the viscous fluid that fills living cells, where the glycolytic reactions take place.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] The citric acid cycle, also known as the Krebs cycle or the TCA (tricarboxylic acid) cycle is an 8-step process that takes the pyruvate generated by glycolysis and generates 4 NADH, FADH2, and GTP, which is further converted to ATP.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] It is only in step 5, where GTP is generated, by succinyl-CoA synthetase, and then converted to ATP, that ADP is used (GTP + ADP → GDP + ATP).
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] Oxidative phosphorylation produces 26 of the 30 equivalents of ATP generated in cellular respiration by transferring electrons from NADH or FADH2 to O2 through electron carriers.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy released when electrons are passed from higher-energy NADH or FADH2 to the lower-energy O2 is required to phosphorylate ADP and once again generate ATP.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] It is this energy coupling and phosphorylation of ADP to ATP that gives the electron transport chain the name oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] During the initial phases of glycolysis and the TCA cycle, cofactors such as NAD+ donate and accept electrons that aid in the electron transport chain's ability to produce a proton gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] The ATP synthase complex exists within the mitochondrial membrane (FO portion) and protrudes into the matrix (F1 portion).
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy derived as a result of the chemical gradient is then used to synthesize ATP by coupling the reaction of inorganic phosphate to ADP in the active site of the ATP synthase enzyme; the equation for this can be written as ADP + Pi → ATP.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] Under normal conditions, small disk-shape platelets circulate in the blood freely and without interaction with one another.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP is stored in dense bodies inside blood platelets and is released upon platelet activation.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP interacts with a family of ADP receptors found on platelets (P2Y1, P2Y12, and P2X1), which leads to platelet activation.
[src:anabolism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP in the blood is converted to adenosine by the action of ecto-ADPases, inhibiting further platelet activation via adenosine receptors.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] If the electron acceptor is oxygen, the process is more specifically known as aerobic cellular respiration.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] If the electron acceptor is a molecule other than oxygen, this is anaerobic cellular respiration – not to be confused with fermentation, which is also an anaerobic process, but it is not respiration, as no external electron acceptor is involved.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The reactions involved in respiration are catabolic reactions, which break large molecules into smaller ones, producing ATP.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Respiration is one of the key ways a cell releases chemical energy to fuel cellular activity.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The overall reaction occurs in a series of biochemical steps, some of which are redox reactions.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Although cellular respiration is technically a combustion reaction, it is an unusual one because of the slow, controlled release of energy from the series of reactions.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Nutrients that are commonly used by animal and plant cells in respiration include sugar, amino acids and fatty acids, and the most common oxidizing agent is molecular oxygen (O2).
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The negative ΔG indicates that the reaction is exothermic (exergonic) and can occur spontaneously.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The potential of NADH and FADH2 is converted to more ATP through an electron transport chain with oxygen and protons (hydrogen ions) as the "terminal electron acceptors".
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Most of the ATP produced by aerobic cellular respiration is made by oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The energy released is used to create a chemiosmotic potential by pumping protons across a membrane.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] This potential is then used to drive ATP synthase and produce ATP from ADP and a phosphate group.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Biology textbooks often state that 38 ATP molecules can be made per oxidized glucose molecule during cellular respiration (2 from glycolysis, 2 from the Krebs cycle, and about 34 from the electron transport system).
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] However, this maximum yield is never quite reached because of losses due to leaky membranes as well as the cost of moving pyruvate and ADP into the mitochondrial matrix, and current estimates range around 29 to 30 ATP per glucose.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Aerobic metabolism is up to 15 times more efficient than anaerobic metabolism (which yields 2 molecules of ATP per 1 molecule of glucose).
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] However, some anaerobic organisms, such as methanogens are able to continue with anaerobic respiration, yielding more ATP by using inorganic molecules other than oxygen as final electron acceptors in the electron transport chain.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] They share the initial pathway of glycolysis but aerobic metabolism continues with the Krebs cycle and oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The post-glycolytic reactions take place in the mitochondria in eukaryotic cells, and in the cytoplasm in prokaryotic cells.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Although plants are net consumers of carbon dioxide and producers of oxygen via photosynthesis, plant respiration accounts for about half of the CO2 generated annually by terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Glycolysis is a metabolic pathway that takes place in the cytosol of cells in all living organisms.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Glycolysis can be literally translated as "sugar splitting", and occurs regardless of oxygen's presence or absence.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The process converts one molecule of glucose into two molecules of pyruvate (pyruvic acid), generating energy in the form of two net molecules of ATP.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Four molecules of ATP per glucose are actually produced, but two are consumed as part of the preparatory phase.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The initial phosphorylation of glucose is required to increase the reactivity (decrease its stability) in order for the molecule to be cleaved into two pyruvate molecules by the enzyme aldolase.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] During the pay-off phase of glycolysis, four phosphate groups are transferred to four ADP by substrate-level phosphorylation to make four ATP, and two NADH are also produced during the pay-off phase.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Starting with glucose, 1 ATP is used to donate a phosphate to glucose to produce glucose 6-phosphate.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Glycogen can be converted into glucose 6-phosphate as well with the help of glycogen phosphorylase.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] During energy metabolism, glucose 6-phosphate becomes fructose 6-phosphate.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] An additional ATP is used to phosphorylate fructose 6-phosphate into fructose 1,6-bisphosphate by the help of phosphofructokinase.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Fructose 1,6-biphosphate then splits into two phosphorylated molecules with three carbon chains which later degrades into pyruvate.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Pyruvate is oxidized to acetyl-CoA and CO2 by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC).
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The PDC contains multiple copies of three enzymes and is located in the mitochondria of eukaryotic cells and in the cytosol of prokaryotes.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] In the conversion of pyruvate to acetyl-CoA, one molecule of NADH and one molecule of CO2 is formed.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The citric acid cycle is also called the *Krebs cycle* or the *tricarboxylic acid cycle*.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] When oxygen is present, acetyl-CoA is produced from the pyruvate molecules created from glycolysis.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Once acetyl-CoA is formed, aerobic or anaerobic respiration can occur.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] When oxygen is present, the mitochondria will undergo aerobic respiration which leads to the Krebs cycle.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] However, if oxygen is not present, fermentation of the pyruvate molecule will occur.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] In the presence of oxygen, when acetyl-CoA is produced, the molecule then enters the citric acid cycle (Krebs cycle) inside the mitochondrial matrix, and is oxidized to CO2 while at the same time reducing NAD to NADH.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] NADH can be used by the electron transport chain to create further ATP as part of oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] To fully oxidize the equivalent of one glucose molecule, two acetyl-CoA must be metabolized by the Krebs cycle.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Two low-energy waste products, H2O and CO2, are created during this cycle.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The citric acid cycle is an 8-step process involving 18 different enzymes and co-enzymes.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] During the cycle, acetyl-CoA (2 carbons) + oxaloacetate (4 carbons) yields citrate (6 carbons), which is rearranged to a more reactive form called isocitrate (6 carbons).
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Isocitrate is modified to become α-ketoglutarate (5 carbons), succinyl-CoA, succinate, fumarate, malate and, finally, oxaloacetate.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The net gain from one cycle is 3 NADH and 1 FADH2 as hydrogen (proton plus electron) carrying compounds and 1 high-energy GTP, which may subsequently be used to produce ATP.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Thus, the total yield from 1 glucose molecule (2 pyruvate molecules) is 6 NADH, 2 FADH2, and 2 ATP.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] In eukaryotes, oxidative phosphorylation occurs in the mitochondrial cristae.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] It comprises the electron transport chain that establishes a proton gradient (chemiosmotic potential) across the boundary of the inner membrane by oxidizing the NADH produced from the Krebs cycle.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] ATP is synthesized by the ATP synthase enzyme when the chemiosmotic gradient is used to drive the phosphorylation of ADP.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The electrons are finally transferred to exogenous oxygen and, with the addition of two protons, water is formed.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The table below describes the reactions involved when one glucose molecule is fully oxidized into carbon dioxide.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] It is assumed that all the reduced coenzymes are oxidized by the electron transport chain and used for oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Although there is a theoretical yield of 38 ATP molecules per glucose during cellular respiration, such conditions are generally not realized because of losses such as the cost of moving pyruvate (from glycolysis), phosphate, and ADP (substrates for ATP synthesis) into the mitochondria.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] All are actively transported using carriers that utilize the stored energy in the proton electrochemical gradient.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The outcome of these transport processes using the proton electrochemical gradient is that more than 3 H+ are needed to make 1 ATP.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Obviously, this reduces the theoretical efficiency of the whole process and the likely maximum is closer to 28–30 ATP molecules.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] In practice the efficiency may be even lower because the inner membrane of the mitochondria is slightly leaky to protons.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Other factors may also dissipate the proton gradient creating an apparently leaky mitochondria.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] An uncoupling protein known as thermogenin is expressed in some cell types and is a channel that can transport protons.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] When this protein is active in the inner membrane it short circuits the coupling between the electron transport chain and ATP synthesis.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The potential energy from the proton gradient is not used to make ATP but generates heat.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] This is particularly important in brown fat thermogenesis of newborn and hibernating mammals.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] ATP synthase is a key enzyme in cellular respiration that produces ATP using the proton gradient in mitochondria.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] If temperature deviates too far from the optimal range, enzyme activity decreases, reducing ATP production.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] This limits the ability of effectors such as muscles and glands to function, threatening homeostasis.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] These figures may still require further tweaking as new structural details become available.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The above value of 3 H+ / ATP for the synthase assumes that the synthase translocates 9 protons, and produces 3 ATP, per rotation.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The number of protons depends on the number of c subunits in the Fo c-ring, and it is now known that this is 10 in yeast Fo and 8 for vertebrates.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Including one H+ for the transport reactions, this means that synthesis of one ATP requires 1 + 10/3 = 4.33 protons in yeast and 1 + 8/3 = 3.67 in vertebrates.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] This would imply that in human mitochondria the 10 protons from oxidizing NADH would produce 2.72 ATP (instead of 2.5) and the 6 protons from oxidizing succinate or ubiquinol would produce 1.64 ATP (instead of 1.5).
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] This is consistent with experimental results within the margin of error described in a recent review.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The total ATP yield in ethanol or lactic acid fermentation is only 2 molecules coming from glycolysis, because pyruvate is not transferred to the mitochondrion and finally oxidized to the carbon dioxide (CO2), but reduced to ethanol or lactic acid in the cytoplasm.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Without oxygen, pyruvate (pyruvic acid) is not metabolized by cellular respiration but undergoes a process of fermentation.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The pyruvate is not transported into the mitochondrion but remains in the cytoplasm, where it is converted to waste products that may be removed from the cell.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] This serves the purpose of oxidizing the electron carriers so that they can perform glycolysis again and removing the excess pyruvate.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Fermentation oxidizes NADH to NAD+ so it can be re-used in glycolysis.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] In the absence of oxygen, fermentation prevents the buildup of NADH in the cytoplasm and provides NAD+ for glycolysis.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] This waste product varies depending on the organism.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] In skeletal muscles, the waste product is lactic acid.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] This type of fermentation is called lactic acid fermentation.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] In strenuous exercise, when energy demands exceed energy supply, the respiratory chain cannot process all of the hydrogen atoms joined by NADH.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] During anaerobic glycolysis, NAD+ regenerates when pairs of hydrogen combine with pyruvate to form lactate.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Lactate formation is catalyzed by lactate dehydrogenase in a reversible reaction.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Lactate can also be used as an indirect precursor for liver glycogen.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] During recovery, when oxygen becomes available, NAD+ attaches to hydrogen from lactate to form ATP.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] In yeast, the waste products are ethanol and carbon dioxide.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] This type of fermentation is known as alcoholic or ethanol fermentation.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] The ATP generated in this process is made by substrate-level phosphorylation, which does not require oxygen.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Fermentation is less efficient at using the energy from glucose: only 2 ATP are produced per glucose, compared to the 38 ATP per glucose nominally produced by aerobic respiration.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] Glycolytic ATP, however, is produced more quickly.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] For prokaryotes to continue a rapid growth rate when they are shifted from an aerobic environment to an anaerobic environment, they must increase the rate of the glycolytic reactions.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] In July 2019, a scientific study of Kidd Mine in Canada discovered sulfur-breathing organisms which live 7900 feet (2400 meters) below the surface.
[src:anabolism/aerobic-respiration] These organisms are also remarkable because they consume minerals such as pyrite as their food source.
[src:anabolism/alanine] Under biological conditions, alanine exists in its zwitterionic form with its amine group protonated (as −NH+3) and its carboxyl group deprotonated (as −CO−2).
[src:anabolism/alanine] Alanine is encoded by all codons starting with GC (GCU, GCC, GCA, and GCG).
[src:anabolism/alanine] The L-isomer of alanine (left-handed) is the one that is incorporated into proteins.
[src:anabolism/alanine] L-alanine is second only to L-leucine in rate of occurrence, accounting for 7.8% of the primary structure in a sample of 1,150 proteins.
[src:anabolism/alanine] The right-handed form, D-alanine, occurs in peptides in some bacterial cell walls (in peptidoglycan) and in some peptide antibiotics, and occurs in the tissues of many crustaceans and molluscs as an osmolyte.
[src:anabolism/alanine] Alanine is not an essential amino acid in humans because it can be synthesized metabolically and does not need to be present in the diet.
[src:anabolism/alanine] However hypoalaninemia (alanine deficiency) is possible under certain conditions such as ketotic hypoglycemia.
[src:anabolism/alanine] Alanine was first synthesized in 1850 when Adolph Strecker combined acetaldehyde and ammonia with hydrogen cyanide.
[src:anabolism/alanine] The amino acid was named *Alanin* in German, in reference to aldehyde, with the interfix *-an-* for ease of pronunciation, the German ending *-in* used in chemical compounds being analogous to English *-ine*.
[src:anabolism/alanine] Alanine is an aliphatic amino acid, because the side-chain connected to the α-carbon atom is a methyl group (-CH3).
[src:anabolism/alanine] Alanine is the simplest α-amino acid after glycine.
[src:anabolism/alanine] The methyl side-chain of alanine is non-reactive and is therefore hardly ever directly involved in protein function.
[src:anabolism/alanine] Alanine is a nonessential amino acid, meaning it can be manufactured by the human body, and does not need to be obtained through the diet.
[src:anabolism/alanine] Alanine is found in a wide variety of foods, but is particularly concentrated in meats.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Polymerization, an anabolic pathway used to build macromolecules such as nucleic acids, proteins, and polysaccharides, uses condensation reactions to join monomers.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Macromolecules are created from smaller molecules using enzymes and cofactors.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Anabolism is powered by catabolism, where large molecules are broken down into smaller parts and then used up in cellular respiration.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Many anabolic processes are powered by the cleavage of adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Anabolism usually involves reduction and decreases entropy, making it unfavorable without energy input.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] The starting materials, called the precursor molecules, are joined using the chemical energy made available from hydrolyzing ATP, reducing the cofactors NAD+, NADP+, and FAD, or performing other favorable side reactions.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Occasionally it can also be driven by entropy without energy input, in cases like the formation of the phospholipid bilayer of a cell, where hydrophobic interactions aggregate the molecules.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] The reducing agents NADH, NADPH, and FADH2, as well as metal ions, act as cofactors at various steps in anabolic pathways.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] NADH, NADPH, and FADH2 act as electron carriers, while charged metal ions within enzymes stabilize charged functional groups on substrates.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Substrates for anabolism are mostly intermediates taken from catabolic pathways during periods of high energy charge in the cell.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Anabolic processes build organs and tissues.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] These processes produce growth and differentiation of cells and increase in body size, a process that involves synthesis of complex molecules.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Examples of anabolic processes include the growth and mineralization of bone and increases in muscle mass.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Endocrinologists have traditionally classified hormones as anabolic or catabolic, depending on which part of metabolism they stimulate.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] The classic anabolic hormones are the anabolic steroids, which stimulate protein synthesis and muscle growth, and especially insulin, which is the main anabolic hormone of the body, regulating the metabolism of protein, carbohydrates, and fats.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Photosynthetic carbohydrate synthesis in plants and certain bacteria is an anabolic process that produces glucose, cellulose, starch, lipids, and proteins from CO2.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] It uses the energy produced from the light-driven reactions of photosynthesis, and creates the precursors to these large molecules via carbon assimilation in the photosynthetic carbon reduction cycle, a.k.a. the Calvin cycle.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] All amino acids are formed from intermediates in the catabolic processes of glycolysis, the citric acid cycle, or the pentose phosphate pathway.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] From the citric acid cycle, α-ketoglutarate is converted into glutamate and subsequently glutamine, proline, and arginine; and oxaloacetate is converted into aspartate and subsequently asparagine, methionine, threonine, and lysine.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] During periods of high blood sugar, glucose 6-phosphate from glycolysis is diverted to the glycogen-storing pathway.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] It is changed to glucose-1-phosphate by phosphoglucomutase and then to UDP-glucose by UTP--glucose-1-phosphate uridylyltransferase.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Glycogen synthase adds this UDP-glucose to a glycogen chain.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Glucagon is traditionally a catabolic hormone, but also stimulates the anabolic process of gluconeogenesis by the liver, and to a lesser extent the kidney cortex and intestines, during starvation to prevent low blood sugar.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] It is the process of converting pyruvate into glucose.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Pyruvate can come from the breakdown of glucose, lactate, amino acids, or glycerol.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] The gluconeogenesis pathway has many reversible enzymatic processes in common with glycolysis, but it is not the process of glycolysis in reverse.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] It uses different irreversible enzymes to ensure the overall pathway runs in one direction only.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] Anabolism operates with separate enzymes from catalysis, which undergo irreversible steps at some point in their pathways.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] This allows the cell to regulate the rate of production and prevent an infinite loop, also known as a futile cycle, from forming with catabolism.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] The balance between anabolism and catabolism is sensitive to ADP and ATP, otherwise known as the energy charge of the cell.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] High amounts of ATP cause cells to favor the anabolic pathway and slow catabolic activity, while excess ADP slows anabolism and favors catabolism.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] These pathways are also regulated by circadian rhythms, with processes such as glycolysis fluctuating to match an animal's normal periods of activity throughout the day.
[src:anabolism/anabolism] The word *anabolism* is from Neo-Latin, with roots from Ancient Greek: ἀνά, "upward" and βάλλειν, "to throw".
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Anhydridic bonds are often labelled as "*high-energy bonds"*.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] P-O bonds are in fact fairly strong (~30 kJ/mol stronger than C-N bonds) and themselves not particularly easy to break.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] As noted below, energy is released by the hydrolysis of ATP.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] However, when the P-O bonds are broken, *input* of energy is required.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] It is the formation of new bonds and lower-energy inorganic phosphate with a *release of a larger amount of energy* that lowers the total energy of the system and makes it more stable.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Hydrolysis of the phosphate groups in ATP is especially exergonic, because the resulting inorganic phosphate molecular ion is greatly stabilized by multiple resonance structures, making the products (ADP and Pi) lower in energy than the reactant (ATP).
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] The high negative charge density associated with the three adjacent phosphate units of ATP also destabilizes the molecule, making it higher in energy.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Hydrolysis relieves some of these electrostatic repulsions, liberating useful energy in the process by causing conformational changes in enzyme structure.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] In humans, approximately 60 percent of the energy released from the hydrolysis of ATP produces metabolic heat rather than fuel the actual reactions taking place.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Due to the acid-base properties of ATP, ADP, and inorganic phosphate, the hydrolysis of ATP has the effect of lowering the pH of the reaction medium.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Under certain conditions, high levels of ATP hydrolysis can contribute to lactic acidosis.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Hydrolysis of the terminal phosphoanhydridic bond is a highly exergonic process.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] The amount of released energy depends on the conditions in a particular cell.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Specifically, the energy released is dependent on concentrations of ATP, ADP and Pi.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] As the concentrations of these molecules deviate from values at equilibrium, the value of Gibbs free energy change (Δ*G*) will be increasingly different.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] In standard conditions (ATP, ADP and Pi concentrations are equal to 1M, water concentration is equal to 55 M) the value of Δ*G* is between -28 and -34 kJ/mol.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] The range of the Δ*G* value exists because this reaction is dependent on the concentration of Mg2+ cations, which stabilize the ATP molecule.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] The cellular environment also contributes to differences in the Δ*G* value since ATP hydrolysis is dependent not only on the studied cell, but also on the surrounding tissue and even the compartment within the cell.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Variability in the Δ*G* values is therefore to be expected.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] The relationship between the standard Gibbs free energy change Δr*G*o and chemical equilibrium is revealing.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] This relationship is defined by the equation Δr*G*o = -*RT* ln(*K*), where *K* is the equilibrium constant, which is equal to the reaction quotient *Q* in equilibrium.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] The standard value of Δ*G* for this reaction is, as mentioned, between -28 and -34 kJ/mol; however, experimentally determined concentrations of the involved molecules reveal that the reaction is not at equilibrium.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Given this fact, a comparison between the equilibrium constant, *K*, and the reaction quotient, *Q*, provides insight.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] *K* takes into consideration reactions taking place in standard conditions, but in the cellular environment the concentrations of the involved molecules (namely, ATP, ADP, and Pi) are far from the standard 1 M.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] In fact, the concentrations are more appropriately measured in mM, which is smaller than M by three orders of magnitude.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Using these nonstandard concentrations, the calculated value of *Q* is much less than one.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] By relating *Q* to Δ*G* using the equation Δ*G* = Δr*G*o + *RT* ln(*Q*), where Δr*G*o is the standard change in Gibbs free energy for the hydrolysis of ATP, it is found that the magnitude of Δ*G* is much greater than the standard value.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] The nonstandard conditions of the cell actually result in a more favorable reaction.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] In one particular study, to determine Δ*G* in vivo in humans, the concentration of ATP, ADP, and Pi was measured using nuclear magnetic resonance.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] In human muscle cells at rest, the concentration of ATP was found to be around 4 mM and the concentration of ADP was around 9 μM.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Inputing these values into the above equations yields Δ*G* = -64 kJ/mol.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] After ischemia, when the muscle is recovering from exercise, the concentration of ATP is as low as 1 mM and the concentration of ADP is around 7 μM.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] Therefore, the absolute Δ*G* would be as high as -69 kJ/mol.
[src:anabolism/atp-hydrolysis] By comparing the standard value of Δ*G* and the experimental value of Δ*G*, one can see that the energy released from the hydrolysis of ATP, as measured in humans, is almost twice as much as the energy produced under standard conditions.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] ATP synthase lies across a cellular membrane and forms an aperture that protons can cross from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration, imparting energy for the synthesis of ATP.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] This electrochemical gradient is generated by the electron transport chain and allows cells to store energy in ATP for later use.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] In prokaryotic cells ATP synthase lies across the plasma membrane, while in eukaryotic cells it lies across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Organisms capable of photosynthesis also have ATP synthase across the thylakoid membrane, which in plants is located in the chloroplast and in cyanobacteria is located in the cytoplasm.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] ATP synthase is present in all organisms studied.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Eukaryotic ATP synthases are F-ATPases (which usually work as ATP synthases instead of ATPases in cellular environments) and running "in reverse" for an ATPase (ATPases catalyze the decomposition of ATP into ADP and a free phosphate ion).
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] This article deals mainly with this type.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] An F-ATPase consists of two main subunits, FO and F1, which has a rotational motor mechanism allowing for ATP production.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The F1 fraction derives its name from the term "Fraction 1" and FO (written as a subscript letter "o", not "zero") derives its name from being the binding fraction for oligomycin, a type of naturally derived antibiotic that is able to inhibit the FO unit of ATP synthase.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] These functional regions consist of different protein subunits — refer to tables.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] This enzyme is used in synthesis of ATP through aerobic respiration.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Located within the thylakoid membrane and the inner mitochondrial membrane, ATP synthase consists of two regions FO and F1.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] FO causes rotation of F1 and is made of c-ring and subunits a, two b, F6.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] F1 has a water-soluble part that can hydrolyze ATP.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] FO on the other hand has mainly hydrophobic regions.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] FO F1 creates a pathway for protons movement across the membrane.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The F1 portion of ATP synthase is hydrophilic and responsible for hydrolyzing ATP.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The F1 unit protrudes into the cytoplasm (matrix and stroma in mitochondria and chloroplasts respectively).
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Subunits α and β make a hexamer with 6 binding sites.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Three of them are catalytically inactive and they bind ADP.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Three other subunits catalyze the ATP synthesis.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The other F1 subunits γ, δ, and ε are a part of a rotational motor mechanism (rotor/axle).
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The γ subunit allows β to go through conformational changes (i.e., closed, half open, and open states) that allow for ATP to be bound and released once synthesized.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The F1 particle is large and can be seen in the transmission electron microscope by negative staining.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] These are particles of 9 nm diameter that pepper the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] FO is a water insoluble protein with eight subunits and a transmembrane ring.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The FO region of ATP synthase is a proton pore that is embedded in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] It consists of three main subunits, a, b, and c.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Six c subunits make up the rotor ring, and subunit b makes up a stalk connecting to F1 OSCP that prevents the αβ hexamer from rotating.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Humans have six additional subunits, d, e, f, g, F6, and 8 (or A6L).
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] This part of the enzyme is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and couples proton translocation to the rotation that causes ATP synthesis in the F1 region.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] In eukaryotes, mitochondrial FO forms membrane-bending dimers.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] These dimers self-arrange into long rows at the end of the cristae, possibly the first step of cristae formation.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] An atomic model for the dimeric yeast FO region was determined by cryo-EM at an overall resolution of 3.6 Å.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] In the 1960s through the 1970s, Paul Boyer, a UCLA Professor, developed the binding change, or flip-flop, mechanism theory, which postulated that ATP synthesis is dependent on a conformational change in ATP synthase generated by rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Walker, then at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge, crystallized the F1 catalytic-domain of ATP synthase.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The structure, at the time the largest asymmetric protein structure known, indicated that Boyer's rotary-catalysis model was, in essence, correct.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] For elucidating this, Boyer and Walker shared half of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The crystal structure of the F1 showed alternating alpha and beta subunits (3 of each), arranged like segments of an orange around a rotating asymmetrical gamma subunit.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] A portion of the FO (the ring of c-subunits) rotates as the protons pass through the membrane.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The c-ring is tightly attached to the asymmetric central stalk (consisting primarily of the gamma subunit), causing it to rotate within the alpha3beta3 of F1 causing the 3 catalytic nucleotide binding sites to go through a series of conformational changes that lead to ATP synthesis.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The major F1 subunits are prevented from rotating in sympathy with the central stalk rotor by a peripheral stalk that joins the alpha3beta3 to the non-rotating portion of FO.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The structure of the intact ATP synthase is currently known at low-resolution from electron cryo-microscopy (cryo-EM) studies of the complex.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The cryo-EM model of ATP synthase suggests that the peripheral stalk is a flexible structure that wraps around the complex as it joins F1 to FO.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Under the right conditions, the enzyme reaction can also be carried out in reverse, with ATP hydrolysis driving proton pumping across the membrane.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The binding change mechanism involves the active site of a β subunit's cycling between three states.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] In the "loose" state, ADP and phosphate enter the active site; in the adjacent diagram, this is shown in pink.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The enzyme then undergoes a change in shape and forces these molecules together, with the active site in the resulting "tight" state (shown in red) binding the newly produced ATP molecule with very high affinity.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Finally, the active site cycles back to the open state (orange), releasing ATP and binding more ADP and phosphate, ready for the next cycle of ATP production.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Like other enzymes, the activity of F1FO ATP synthase is reversible.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Large-enough quantities of ATP cause it to create a transmembrane proton gradient, this is used by fermenting bacteria that do not have an electron transport chain, but rather hydrolyze ATP to make a proton gradient, which they use to drive flagella and the transport of nutrients into the cell.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] In respiring bacteria under physiological conditions, ATP synthase, in general, runs in the opposite direction, creating ATP while using the proton motive force created by the electron transport chain as a source of energy.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The overall process of creating energy in this fashion is termed oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The same process takes place in the mitochondria, where ATP synthase is located in the inner mitochondrial membrane and the F1-part projects into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] By pumping proton cations into the matrix, the ATP-synthase converts ADP into ATP.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The evolution of ATP synthase is thought to have been modular whereby two functionally independent subunits became associated and gained new functionality.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] This association appears to have occurred early in evolutionary history, because essentially the same structure and activity of ATP synthase enzymes are present in all kingdoms of life.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The F-ATP synthase displays high functional and mechanistic similarity to the V-ATPase.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] However, whereas the F-ATP synthase generates ATP by utilising a proton gradient, the V-ATPase generates a proton gradient at the expense of ATP, generating pH values of as low as 1.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The F1 region also shows significant similarity to hexameric DNA helicases (especially the Rho factor), and the entire enzyme region shows some similarity to H+ -powered T3SS or flagellar motor complexes.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The α3β3 hexamer of the F1 region shows significant structural similarity to hexameric DNA helicases; both form a ring with 3-fold rotational symmetry with a central pore.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The H+ motor of the FO particle shows great functional similarity to the H+ motors that drive flagella.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Both feature a ring of many small alpha-helical proteins that rotate relative to nearby stationary proteins, using a H+ potential gradient as an energy source.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] This link is tenuous, however, as the overall structure of flagellar motors is far more complex than that of the FO particle and the ring with about 30 rotating proteins is far larger than the 10, 11, or 14 helical proteins in the FO complex.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] More recent structural data do however show that the ring and the stalk are structurally similar to the F1 particle.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The modular evolution theory for the origin of ATP synthase suggests that two subunits with independent function, a DNA helicase with ATPase activity and a H+ motor, were able to bind, and the rotation of the motor drove the ATPase activity of the helicase in reverse.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] This complex then evolved greater efficiency and eventually developed into today's intricate ATP synthases.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Alternatively, the DNA helicase/H+ motor complex may have had H+ pump activity with the ATPase activity of the helicase driving the H+ motor in reverse.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] This may have evolved to carry out the reverse reaction and act as an ATP synthase.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] A variety of natural and synthetic inhibitors of ATP synthase have been discovered.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] These have been used to probe the structure and mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] There are several classes of ATP synthase inhibitors, including peptide inhibitors, polyphenolic phytochemicals, polyketides, organotin compounds, polyenic α-pyrone derivatives, cationic inhibitors, substrate analogs, amino acid modifiers, and other miscellaneous chemicals.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Some of the most commonly used ATP synthase inhibitors are oligomycin and DCCD.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Bacterial F-ATPases can occasionally operate in reverse, turning them into an ATPase.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Some bacteria have no F-ATPase, using an A/V-type ATPase bidirectionally.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Yeast ATP synthase is one of the best-studied eukaryotic ATP synthases; and five F1, eight FO subunits, and seven associated proteins have been identified.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Most of these proteins have homologues in other eukaryotes.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] In plants, ATP synthase is also present in chloroplasts (CF1FO-ATP synthase).
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The enzyme is integrated into thylakoid membrane; the CF1-part sticks into stroma, where dark reactions of photosynthesis (also called the light-independent reactions or the Calvin cycle) and ATP synthesis take place.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The overall structure and the catalytic mechanism of the chloroplast ATP synthase are almost the same as those of the bacterial enzyme.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] However, in chloroplasts, the proton motive force is generated not by respiratory electron transport chain but by primary photosynthetic proteins.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The synthase has a 40-aa insert in the gamma-subunit to inhibit wasteful activity when dark.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The ATP synthase isolated from bovine (*Bos taurus*) heart mitochondria is, in terms of biochemistry and structure, the best-characterized ATP synthase.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Beef heart is used as a source for the enzyme because of the high concentration of mitochondria in cardiac muscle.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Their genes have close homology to human ATP synthases.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Eukaryotes belonging to some divergent lineages have very special organizations of the ATP synthase.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] A euglenozoa ATP synthase forms a dimer with a boomerang-shaped F1 head like other mitochondrial ATP synthases, but the FO subcomplex has many unique subunits.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] The inhibitory IF1 also binds differently, in a way shared with trypanosomatida.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Apicomplexans, such as *Plasmodium*, utilise a hexameric ATP synthase organisation existing as a trimer of ATP synthase dimers.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] These hexameric assemblies arrange into pentagonal pyramids, which induce a unique bulbous cristae membrane morphology.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] This organisation is underpinned by both apicomplexan-specific subunits and cardiolipins.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Archaea do not generally have an F-ATPase.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Instead, they synthesize ATP using the A-ATPase/synthase, a rotary machine structurally similar to the V-ATPase but mainly functioning as an ATP synthase.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] Like the bacteria F-ATPase, it is believed to also function as an ATPase.
[src:anabolism/atp-synthase] F-ATPase gene linkage and gene order are widely conserved across ancient prokaryote lineages, implying that this system already existed at a date before the last universal common ancestor, the LUCA.
